Good morning,

On yesterday=E2=80=99s episode of Sharp Tech ( https://sharptech.fm/member/=
episode/an-endgame-for-you-tube-tv-big-disney-decisions-and-whether-bob-ige=
r-should-make-them-the-era-beyond-peak-tv ) we thought we wrapped up our on=
going discussion about the changes in TV inspired by the Disney-Charter sho=
wdown with a focus on Google and YouTube TV, and Disney=E2=80=99s options g=
oing forward. As you shall soon see, though, the news is still coming on bo=
th fronts.

On to the Update:

Max Gets Sports
---------------

From the Hollywood Reporter ( https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/di=
gital/max-streaming-sports-tier-price-launch-1235593906/ ) :

Live sports are coming to Max next month. The Warner Bros. Discovery-owned =
streaming platform will launch a new premium sports tier Oct. 5, just in ti=
me for the Major League Baseball playoffs, which start two days later. The =
new tier will be called the Bleacher Report Sports Add-On (or B/R Sports), =
taking the name of WBD=E2=80=99s digital sports news, opinion and highlight=
s brand. It will cost $10 per month on top of the subscription for Max, how=
ever it will be available for free during a promotional period that runs th=
rough the end of February, covering the MLB playoffs, and much of the NBA a=
nd NHL seasons.

=E2=80=9CPart of our thinking about setting the $9.99 monthly price and an =
upcharge to it, is we don=E2=80=99t think the way that it=E2=80=99s current=
ly being done in streaming where most of the other streamers are just givin=
g away the content for free is viable for the long term, number one, and nu=
mber two it disadvantages and almost incentivizes the switch [from pay TV t=
o streaming] which is not something that we=E2=80=99re necessarily looking =
to do,=E2=80=9D says JB Perrette, the CEO for global streaming and games at=
 Warner Bros. Discovery, in an interview with The Hollywood Reporter.

=E2=80=9C[We thought] if we=E2=80=99re gonna do this, let=E2=80=99s do it i=
n a way that is very much a compelling proposition to viewers,=E2=80=9D add=
s WBD Sports chairman and CEO Luis Silberwasser. =E2=80=9CSo we purposely d=
ecided we=E2=80=99re going to give consumers the same choice in terms of th=
e live games, but you don=E2=80=99t have to sacrifice pay TV to go watch on=
 Max, or vice versa.=E2=80=9D

The company says that all told, it will stream more than 300 live games eac=
h year, as well as Bleacher Report live video content and library fare. WBD=
 Sports has rights to MLB, NBA and NHL games (including the playoffs and ev=
ents like the NHL Winter Classic), as well as NCAA March Madness basketball=
, U.S. National Team soccer and WBD=E2=80=99s own golf brand, The Match=E2=
=80=A6

=E2=80=9CPart of the strategy to try and gain incremental reach is to try t=
o attract the younger viewers who are most likely to be leaving that pay-TV=
 ecosystem,=E2=80=9D Silberwasser says. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re not trying t=
o take anything away and hopefully not incentivizing current people who are=
 on the linear side to move.

A few quick thoughts:

* First, Perrette is correct that streamers (most prominently Peacock) incl=
uding sports rights for a relatively low monthly fee simply isn=E2=80=99t s=
ustainable in the long run; either the monthly subscription fee will have t=
o increase a lot or there will need to be an additional sports tier.
* Second, in a world of streaming, where it is easy to churn, an additional=
 sports tier is probably the correct choice of these two options. General e=
ntertainment can be saved up and binged, which means that a higher price wo=
uld incentivize general entertainment-only consumers to simply dip in-and-o=
ut of Max.
* Third, notice that sports fans have to subscribe to Max first; in other w=
ords, people who only want sports will be effectively subsidizing general e=
ntertainment, which is an inverse of where the traditional cable bundle is =
currently.

As for the numbers, WBD currently pays an average of $2.7 billion/year for =
the NBA ($1.2 billion), NCAA ($770 million), MLB ($470 million) and NHL ($2=
25 million), with the NBA deal up for renewal. Covering those costs would n=
ecessitate more than 22 million subscribers on the sports tier, all of whom=
 stay subscribed year round; if you assume that Max is paying a 30% commiss=
ion on each subscription then the number jumps to 32 million subscribers.

Still, that=E2=80=99s honestly a lower percentage of Max=E2=80=99s ~95 mill=
ion subscribers than I expected (that subscriber number also includes some =
number of international customers); of course WBD is also currently getting=
 most of the value from sports via the cable bundle.

The Fox Linchpin
----------------

WBD actually has a decent argument that this deal isn=E2=80=99t going to hu=
rt the bundle, because the key thing to understand about their rights deals=
 is that WBD doesn=E2=80=99t have exclusive access to any of the major spor=
ts that they televise:

* The NBA is on TNT and ESPN/ABC
* The NCAA=E2=80=99s March Madness is on TNT/TBS/truTV and CBS, and regular=
 season games are also on ESPN, Fox, and FS1
* The NHL is on TNT and ESPN/ESPN+/ABC
* MLB is on TNT/TBS, ESPN, and Fox/FS1

If you=E2=80=99re a sports fan who wants access to every game you still hav=
e to have the full bundle; given that, this tier seems like a reasonable wa=
y to potentially acquire younger users, but it probably won=E2=80=99t make =
that big of a difference in the long run. Where it would really matter, tho=
ugh, is if all of those other channels were available over the top as well.

This does raise the Fox question more broadly. I noted in Charter-Disney Wi=
nners and Losers ( https://stratechery.com/2023/charter-disney-winners-and-=
losers/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nw=
