swNLBg ) , a reader writes:

Byrne [Hobart] mentions that Kroger took in $8.7B in trade spend from suppl=
iers and booked $2B in operating profit. He says (and you quoted): =E2=80=
=9CSo in a sense the default model for the grocery business is that an effi=
cient, well-run grocery store will lose money on the business of selling fo=
od and other consumables to customers, but more than make up for it by sell=
ing direct or indirect ads to the companies that make those products.=E2=80=
=9D This comment implies that the $8.7B pays for a form of advertising, and=
 that=E2=80=99s mostly untrue.

The vast majority =E2=80=94 like 75% =E2=80=94 of trade dollars spent at a =
retailer like Kroger reduces the cost of items for consumers: sale prices a=
nd coupons (everybody), everyday low price (esp. at Walmart), and loyalty-p=
rogram discounts (esp. at Kroger). This trade spend is passed to the custom=
er to boost top-line revenue; it=E2=80=99s not like an ad program that drop=
s revenue to the bottom line.

Less than 10% of trade spend goes toward things that are promotional/shoppe=
r marketing-ish =E2=80=94 things like shelf space, endcaps, sampling and si=
gnage. Those costs are indeed more like advertising, but even among those t=
actics much of the spend goes primarily to third parties (i.e. printers and=
 in-store merchandising companies). The retailer keeps only a portion pf th=
at 10% as profit.

Anyway, I mention this because I=E2=80=99ve seen many tech people equate tr=
ade spend to endcaps to profits. If that were true, then retail would be a =
LOT more profitable than it is.

This is an excellent correction and I=E2=80=99m happy to receive it; it=E2=
=80=99s also good news for Instacart in the long run. Oh, and congrats to I=
nstacart, which closed up 12% ( https://www.cnbc.com/2023/09/19/instacart-s=
